We used linear mixed models (lme) to test the effects of plant and soil origin on aboveground biomass (AGB). We included block as a random factor to account for potential spatial variability within the experimental site. The full model for AGB included all possible interactions between variables:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} lme \, (log\left( {AGB} \right)\,\sim \,soil.origin \, * \, plant.origin \, \quad * \, drought \, * \, inoculum\, + \,height.0, \, random \hfill \\ \, = \,\sim 1|block, \, method = \hbox{''}ML\hbox{''}) \hfill \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}lme(logAGB∼soil.origin∗plant.origin∗drought∗inoculum+height.0,random=∼1|block,method=''ML'')

To analyse mycorrhizal colonization (mycoperc) we used generalized linear models (glm). We treated block as a fixed effect, which allowed us to fit glms instead of mixed models. The full model was then defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
